---
import PageLayout from "../layouts/PageLayout.astro";
---

<PageLayout
  title="My Career"
  description="Twenty years of software engineering — the story behind the résumé."
>
  <header class="mb-10 flex items-start justify-between gap-4">
    <div>
      <h1
        class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100 mb-1"
      >
        My Career
      </h1>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 text-sm">
        Software Engineer · Cloud Architect
      </p>
    </div>
    <a
      href="/KyleDaleyResume.pdf"
      class="shrink-0 inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-md text-sm font-medium bg-brand-600 text-white hover:bg-brand-700 dark:bg-brand-500 dark:hover:bg-brand-400 transition-colors"
      aria-label="Download PDF résumé"
    >
      <svg
        xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
        width="14"
        height="14"
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        stroke-width="2"
        stroke-linecap="round"
        stroke-linejoin="round"
        aria-hidden="true"
      >
        <path d="M21 15v4a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2v-4"></path>
        <polyline points="7 10 12 15 17 10"></polyline>
        <line x1="12" y1="15" x2="12" y2="3"></line>
      </svg>
      PDF
    </a>
  </header>

  <div
    class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none prose-a:text-brand-600 dark:prose-a:text-brand-300 prose-blockquote:border-brand-300 dark:prose-blockquote:border-brand-700"
  >
    <p>This page is a little different than a traditional résumé.</p>

    <p>
      Sure, you can skim it. You can jump to the technologies, <a
        href="/KyleDaleyResume.pdf">download the PDF résumé</a
      >, and move on. There's nothing wrong with that. But that's not really
      what I had in mind when I wrote it.
    </p>

    <p>
      If we ever grab coffee together, there's a pretty good chance this is
      where the conversation ends up anyway. We'll probably start by talking
      about whatever technology we're both interested in at the moment. Before
      long we'll wander into old Microsoft technologies, software architecture,
      managers who shaped my career, projects that never shipped, lessons
      learned the hard way, and chase some rabbits that somehow circle back to
      the original topic.
    </p>

    <p>That's what I wanted this page to feel like.</p>

    <p>
      Not a polished timeline of jobs and titles, but the kind of conversation
      where we're getting to know each other over a couple cups of coffee. We'll
      listen as much as we talk. We'll laugh a little. We'll probably refill our
      mugs more than once. And by the time we're done, I hope you'll have a
      better sense of who I am as an engineer, and maybe as a person, than any
      two-page résumé could ever tell you.
    </p>

    <p>So welcome! I'm glad you're here.</p>

    <blockquote>
      "I want this page to feel like we're having coffee, chasing rabbits, telling stories, and getting to know each other."
    </blockquote>

    <nav
      class="not-prose mb-10 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 dark:border-neutral-800 bg-neutral-50 dark:bg-neutral-900 p-5"
    >
      <h2
        class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 mb-3"
      >
        On this page
      </h2>

      <ol class="space-y-2 text-sm">
        <li><a href="#today">Where I Am Today</a></li>
        <li>
          <a href="#beginning">I Didn't Plan to Become a Software Engineer</a>
        </li>
        <li><a href="#gimmal">Finding My Place</a></li>
        <li><a href="#historian">Becoming the Historian</a></li>
        <li><a href="#platforms">Learning to Build Platforms</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <h2 id="today">Where I Am Today</h2>

    <p>
      My career has never really been about chasing titles or the latest
      technology. It's been a series of opportunities where someone trusted me
      before I felt completely ready, surrounded by people who taught me more
      than they probably realized.
    </p>

    <p>
      I've spent more than twenty years writing software. During that time I've
      lived through desktop applications, SharePoint, Silverlight, cloud
      architecture, containers, and AI-assisted development. The technologies
      have changed constantly.
    </p>

    <p>What hasn't changed is the kind of work I enjoy.</p>

    <p>
      These days I spend most of my time listening. Product, Engineering,
      Customer Success, subject matter experts, stakeholders, and customers all
      have different perspectives. I enjoy taking all of that, understanding the
      systems we already have, and helping teams find a path forward.
    </p>

    <p>Once we've figured that out...</p>

    <p>I still love writing code.</p>

    <p>The rest of this page is how I got here.</p>

    <h2 id="beginning">I Didn't Plan to Become a Software Engineer</h2>

    <p>
      I started writing software in high school back in 1996. My computer
      science teacher, Coach Baker, somehow made programming fun. We wrote Turbo
      Pascal, solved problems, and looked forward to class every day.
    </p>

    <a
      href="/career/origins"
      class="not-prose inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 mb-6 text-sm font-medium text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-400 hover:underline"
    >
      Read the full story: Origins: Hall C →
    </a>

    <p>
      Oddly enough, I left for college convinced I <em>didn't</em> want to become
      a programmer.
    </p>

    <p>
      After struggling through Discrete Math, I changed majors from Computer
      Science to Management Information Systems and figured I'd stay closer to
      the business side of technology.
    </p>

    <p>Funny enough, that's not how things worked out.</p>

    <p>
      My first real opportunity came through a friend who helped me land a job
      at Hanson Building Materials. I wasn't hired as a software developer. In
      fact, I eventually accepted what was supposed to be a DBA position that
      turned out to be little more than glorified data entry.
    </p>

    <p>
      During a project to build a sales quoting application, someone found out
      I'd written software back in high school and asked if I wanted to take a
      crack at writing some code.
    </p>

    <p>I said yes.</p>

    <p>
      I had no experience with .NET, but .NET 2.0 had just been released, so I
      learned as I went. Looking back, that set the tone for the rest of my
      career. I've rarely been the person who already knew everything. More
      often, someone trusted me enough to learn.
    </p>

    <p>
      A few years later I joined Meisel, where I worked on an in-house ERP
      system. I learned a tremendous amount there, both technically and
      professionally. Around that time .NET 4.0 was released, and we were
      fortunate enough to attend the Visual Studio 2010 launch event in Las
      Vegas. I still remember how energized we all were when we came back. It
      felt like there was something new to learn every week.
    </p>

    <p>Somewhere along the way I realized something.</p>

    <p>I actually loved writing software.</p>

    <h2 id="gimmal">Finding My Place</h2>

    <p>In August of 2011 I joined GimmalSoft.</p>

    <p>
      When I started there were four of us in a small office in the Galleria
      Towers. I had an incredible amount to learn. SharePoint. Silverlight. WCF.
      Records management. I remember feeling like I was drinking from a fire
      hose.
    </p>

    <p>
      What I remember even more than the technology, though, are the people.
    </p>

    <p>
      We worked together. If someone had a question, we'd grab a whiteboard.
      Damon and Jeff had years of experience. Jonathan was our architect. None
      of them ever made me feel like I was "just" the junior developer. We
      solved problems together.
    </p>

    <p>
      As the team grew, so did the office. Lunch usually meant everyone piling
      into cars together. More than once we ended up playing Super Smash Bros.
      on a GameCube before getting back to work. Big milestones usually meant
      Fogo de Chão.
    </p>

    <p>It sounds strange to write this on a career page, but it matters.</p>

    <p>
      We watched Jonathan lose his wife to cancer. Later we celebrated his
      marriage to Kari. The team was there when all three of my children were
      born. When my mom passed away, they all came to the funeral.
    </p>

    <p>We weren't just coworkers.</p>

    <p>We were family.</p>

    <blockquote>
      Someday I'd like to write more about this period of my career. It shaped
      me more than any technology ever has.
    </blockquote>

    <h2 id="historian">Becoming the Historian</h2>

    <p>The longer I stayed, the more products I touched.</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Compliance Suite</li>
      <li>Information Governance Suite</li>
      <li>Enterprise Events</li>
      <li>File Plan Builder</li>
      <li>Advanced Content Type Retention</li>
      <li>Unified Records Management</li>
      <li>Physical Inventory Management</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Somewhere along the way I became the person people came to when they
      wanted to understand how all of those systems fit together.
    </p>

    <p>I never really planned for that to happen.</p>

    <p>
      Then Microsoft introduced SharePoint Apps and CSOM, forcing us to rethink
      huge portions of our architecture. Supporting both SharePoint Online and
      on-premises customers wasn't easy, but those years taught me how to think
      beyond individual applications and start thinking about platforms.
    </p>

    <p>Eventually the office closed.</p>

    <p>
      I remember taking my young daughter with me one last time to help box up
      the remaining equipment before turning in the keys.
    </p>

    <p>That was a difficult day.</p>

    <h2 id="platforms">Learning to Build Platforms</h2>

    <p>Before long I was asked to join the SaaS team.</p>

    <p>
      It didn't feel like a promotion. It felt like another opportunity to
      learn.
    </p>

    <p>
      Docker. Azure. .NET Core. Angular. Terraform. Multi-tenancy. Automated
      provisioning.
    </p>

    <p>
      Once again I found myself walking into a room where everyone seemed to
      know more than I did.
    </p>

    <p>That feeling has become surprisingly familiar over the years.</p>

    <p>
      During Program Increment planning we'd spend hours around whiteboards
      talking through ideas before writing a single line of code. One of our
      product managers, Nathan, had a phrase I've carried with me ever since:
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      "I don't care how you architect it. Just don't paint yourselves into a
      corner."
    </blockquote>

    <p>I still think about that advice today.</p>

  </div>
</PageLayout>
